1
00:06:21,831 --> 00:06:23,594
<i>Listen carefully...</i>

2
00:06:23,800 --> 00:06:25,290
<i>... my son.</i>

3
00:06:26,269 --> 00:06:27,600
<i>By now, Kal-El...</i>

4
00:06:27,804 --> 00:06:32,366
<i>... you are entering the atmosphere</i>
<i>of the planet known as Earth.</i>

5
00:06:32,608 --> 00:06:35,372
<i>I pray you have made a safe journey.</i>

6
00:06:36,312 --> 00:06:41,215
<i>The yellow sun of your new home</i>
<i>will give you great physical powers.</i>

7
00:06:41,484 --> 00:06:44,282
<i>But it cannot console your spirit.</i>

8
00:06:45,655 --> 00:06:49,614
<i>Placed aboard this vessel</i>
<i>is an energy module...</i>

9
00:06:49,826 --> 00:06:53,956
<i>... all that remains</i>
<i>of a once-powerful civilization:</i>

10
00:06:54,163 --> 00:06:56,688
<i>Krypton, your mother planet.</i>

11
00:06:56,899 --> 00:06:59,868
<i>It is my last gift to you.</i>

12
00:07:00,436 --> 00:07:05,396
<i>Once removed, the ship will</i>
<i>grow cold and silent...</i>

13
00:07:05,908 --> 00:07:09,002
<i>... and you will be finally alone.</i>

14
00:07:09,278 --> 00:07:13,647
<i>The power in the module</i>
<i>can be used but once.</i>

15
00:07:14,884 --> 00:07:18,581
<i>Use it wisely, my son.</i>

16
00:07:50,019 --> 00:07:52,214
Clark, you out here?

17
00:07:53,156 --> 00:07:54,282
Clark Kent!

18
00:07:55,024 --> 00:07:55,991
Hi, Mr. Hornsby.

19
00:07:56,325 --> 00:07:57,155
Over here.

20
00:07:57,360 --> 00:07:59,225
- There you are.
- How are you, sir?

21
00:07:59,428 --> 00:08:02,556
- I'm fine, Clark. How are you?
- Nice to see you.

22
00:08:02,765 --> 00:08:04,790
- It's been a long time.
- A long time.

23
00:08:05,001 --> 00:08:07,492
I was tidying up for when
you show the place.

24
00:08:07,703 --> 00:08:11,503
Didn't I mention there was
an offer to buy, sight unseen?

25
00:08:11,741 --> 00:08:14,835
I don't want to sell this place
to a big developer.

26
00:08:15,077 --> 00:08:18,877
The buyer has to want a real farm,
not another shopping center.

27
00:08:19,081 --> 00:08:22,016
Now darn it, Clark,
why are you so stubborn?

28
00:08:22,218 --> 00:08:25,517
Today, nobody wants a farm.

29
00:08:25,721 --> 00:08:30,021
You blink your eye and they'll
all be gone. That's progress.

30
00:08:31,827 --> 00:08:34,261
Oh, my gosh, look at this.

31
00:08:36,399 --> 00:08:40,165
Oh, what a joker
old Jonathan Kent was.

32
00:08:40,770 --> 00:08:44,672
You know, I asked him
what happened to the baby's crib.

33
00:08:44,907 --> 00:08:46,465
And he said:

34
00:08:47,243 --> 00:08:52,010
"Oh, little Clark must've had
a bad dream and kicked it."

35
00:08:52,215 --> 00:08:54,649
- I swear, Dad liked a good joke.
- Yeah.

36
00:08:55,651 --> 00:08:59,644
I was wondering, maybe you'd like
to keep these for your grandchildren.

37
00:08:59,855 --> 00:09:02,483
Why, thank you very much, Clark.

38
00:09:03,092 --> 00:09:04,354
Here, batter up.

39
00:09:04,560 --> 00:09:05,458
- Oh, no.
- Come on.

40
00:09:05,661 --> 00:09:07,424
- No, really...
- We'll hit a few.

41
00:09:13,102 --> 00:09:16,037
Watch out now, these will
come in pretty fast.

42
00:09:23,512 --> 00:09:25,742
You never could hit a curve ball!

43
00:09:28,217 --> 00:09:30,617
That's my final decision
about the place.

44
00:09:30,820 --> 00:09:32,811
I'm holding out for a real farmer.

45
00:09:33,189 --> 00:09:34,349
You are?

46
00:09:36,359 --> 00:09:39,328
And you're just as obstinate
as your father was too.

47
00:09:39,528 --> 00:09:41,689
I'm sorry, but that's
just the way it is.

48
00:09:41,897 --> 00:09:44,889
You be careful when you get back
to Metropolis, Clark.

49
00:09:45,901 --> 00:09:48,392
It's a long, long way from
where you were born.

50
00:09:48,604 --> 00:09:51,630
Yes, sir. I never forget that, sir.

51
00:09:54,510 --> 00:09:56,740
- Bye.
- Bye, Clark.

52
00:10:14,997 --> 00:10:18,194
What is that God-awful noise
you're making?

53
00:10:18,701 --> 00:10:22,228
Mozart, my low-forehead friend.

54
00:10:22,471 --> 00:10:26,874
Even this wretched pit can't diminish
the spirit of true genius.

55
00:10:27,543 --> 00:10:30,410
Life itself started in a murky pit
much like this.

56
00:10:31,013 --> 00:10:34,676
A true genius like myself
learns to seize the moment.

57
00:10:35,184 --> 00:10:36,981
You're the first to know...

58
00:10:37,186 --> 00:10:41,623
...that I now have plans
to re-create life itself.

59
00:10:41,957 --> 00:10:46,257
Luthor, start breaking a sweat
or we'll throw you to the wolves.

60
00:10:46,462 --> 00:10:48,521
Luthor, let's get them duds dirty.

61
00:10:48,731 --> 00:10:51,131
- Move it, meathead.
- Let's see a little sweat.

62
00:10:51,334 --> 00:10:52,733
What's that car doing here?!

63
00:10:52,935 --> 00:10:54,800
Stop that vehicle!

64
00:10:57,139 --> 00:10:59,607
- Hey, stop!
- Hold it there, son.

65
00:11:01,043 --> 00:11:05,002
Yo! Where the hell is this and how
the hell do I get to Cedar City?

66
00:11:05,881 --> 00:11:08,247
You on the wrong side
of the state, boy.

67
00:11:08,451 --> 00:11:10,385
- No chance.
- Oh, no.

68
00:11:12,722 --> 00:11:16,920
You got a fine, fine super-fine
sound system here, son.

69
00:11:17,960 --> 00:11:21,828
I guess you dudes have never seen
one of these Sensurround 100s?

70
00:11:22,031 --> 00:11:24,397
Yeah, I seen one once in a magazine.

71
00:11:24,600 --> 00:11:26,898
Well, heck. Come on, get in.

72
00:11:27,636 --> 00:11:28,534
- Really?
- Come on.

73
00:11:28,738 --> 00:11:29,670
Really?

74
00:11:29,905 --> 00:11:32,567
- You wanted to hear it, come on!
- All right.

75
00:11:33,376 --> 00:11:35,867
Hop in, Bubba.
Let's give it a listen.

76
00:11:37,680 --> 00:11:38,908
Hey, this is great!

77
00:11:41,250 --> 00:11:42,740
Doors...

78
00:11:44,387 --> 00:11:45,251
What's going on?

79
00:11:45,454 --> 00:11:46,386
Windows...

80
00:11:48,023 --> 00:11:50,048
- What's happening?
- The top.

81
00:11:50,426 --> 00:11:51,358
Seats!

82
00:11:52,962 --> 00:11:55,362
Lordy! Lordy!

83
00:11:55,731 --> 00:11:57,164
And away!

84
00:12:00,636 --> 00:12:02,194
Y'all come back and see us!

85
00:12:02,405 --> 00:12:03,235
Oh, no!

86
00:12:04,340 --> 00:12:05,773
Launch.

87
00:12:10,780 --> 00:12:12,839
All right!

88
00:12:14,350 --> 00:12:16,910
Did I do okay or what, Uncle Lex?

89
00:12:17,119 --> 00:12:20,953
Lenny, you've always been the
Dutch elm disease of my family tree.

90
00:12:21,157 --> 00:12:22,590
But this time you did fine.

91
00:12:27,163 --> 00:12:29,597
You gonna skip the country, Uncle Lex?

92
00:12:29,865 --> 00:12:31,992
You pathetic product
of the public schools...

93
00:12:32,201 --> 00:12:34,635
...I've had nothing
on my awesome mind...

94
00:12:34,837 --> 00:12:37,328
...since I've been incarcerated
except one thing:

95
00:12:37,573 --> 00:12:40,041
- Destroy Superman!
- Destroy Superman!

96
00:12:44,647 --> 00:12:45,807
Sorry.

97
00:13:01,330 --> 00:13:02,729
Clark!

98
00:13:36,065 --> 00:13:37,362
Help!

99
00:13:37,566 --> 00:13:39,693
Help! Help!

100
00:13:39,902 --> 00:13:41,893
Somebody get help!

101
00:13:57,520 --> 00:13:58,612
Superman!

102
00:14:22,811 --> 00:14:24,540
He's okay. He needs a doctor.

103
00:14:25,714 --> 00:14:27,113
Superman!

104
00:14:27,383 --> 00:14:29,283
Gentlemen, one moment.

105
00:14:29,618 --> 00:14:31,779
I want people to know that
our subway system...

106
00:14:31,987 --> 00:14:35,184
...is the safest and most reliable
means of public transit.

107
00:14:35,391 --> 00:14:36,380
Thank you.

108
00:14:40,429 --> 00:14:41,521
Thanks.

109
00:14:44,266 --> 00:14:45,665
You're late, Kent.

110
00:14:46,068 --> 00:14:48,696
Sorry, Mr. White, won't happen again.

111
00:14:50,005 --> 00:14:51,063
Where is everybody?

112
00:14:51,307 --> 00:14:52,365
Boring.

113
00:14:54,043 --> 00:14:55,567
Tedious.

114
00:14:56,812 --> 00:14:59,178
- Hey, what's going on?
- Abominable!

115
00:14:59,448 --> 00:15:03,475
<i>- Regardez, voilà</i> David Warfield.
- David Warfield...

116
00:15:03,686 --> 00:15:05,586
...who owns those sleazy tabloids?

117
00:15:05,788 --> 00:15:10,589
<i>Au contraire.</i> Who owns all those
sleazy tabloids and <i>The Daily Planet.</i>

118
00:15:11,160 --> 00:15:12,457
Tedious.

119
00:15:12,661 --> 00:15:14,253
You only read the pictures?

120
00:15:14,997 --> 00:15:18,831
The fact is, Mr. White,
that I only read the ledger.

121
00:15:19,034 --> 00:15:23,061
A ledger which the previous owners
paid so little attention to...

122
00:15:23,272 --> 00:15:25,297
...I bought the paper from them.

123
00:15:25,541 --> 00:15:28,806
<i>The Daily Planet</i> hasn't made
any money in three years.

124
00:15:29,111 --> 00:15:31,511
And the name of the game
is making money.

125
00:15:31,947 --> 00:15:36,077
Ladies and gentlemen,
my daughter, Lacy Warfield.

126
00:15:36,285 --> 00:15:38,310
- Thanks, Daddy.
- It's nice to meet you.

127
00:15:39,555 --> 00:15:42,956
Mr. White, Lacy will be helping you.

128
00:15:43,158 --> 00:15:45,126
Helping me? Helping me what?

129
00:15:45,327 --> 00:15:47,955
I have some mock copies
of our new layout.

130
00:15:48,163 --> 00:15:50,154
It's super.

131
00:15:50,366 --> 00:15:52,630
The suit's not right,
but we can change that.

132
00:15:52,835 --> 00:15:54,393
Excuse me, Mr. Warfield.

133
00:15:54,603 --> 00:15:59,097
The world isn't really on the brink.
Isn't that headline irresponsible?

134
00:15:59,341 --> 00:16:01,809
Maybe, but it'll sell
a lot of newspapers.

135
00:16:03,679 --> 00:16:05,408
Mr. White, don't do anything rash.

136
00:16:05,614 --> 00:16:09,380
I won't let you turn this grand
old lady into one of your bimbos...

137
00:16:09,585 --> 00:16:14,284
Mr. White, may I point out that Daddy
holds all of your contracts...

138
00:16:14,490 --> 00:16:16,583
...which you will have to honor.

139
00:16:16,792 --> 00:16:19,192
<i>Excusez-moi,</i> your spoiled-ness...

140
00:16:19,395 --> 00:16:21,056
Why is Lois speaking French?

141
00:16:21,263 --> 00:16:26,030
...I have a plane to catch to Paris for
the emergency Ministers' Conference...

142
00:16:26,235 --> 00:16:29,170
Not so fast. All trips are canceled.

143
00:16:29,571 --> 00:16:32,233
You mean my trip to Paris is canceled?

144
00:16:32,474 --> 00:16:34,635
Mr. White, you come with me.

145
00:16:34,877 --> 00:16:37,675
I want to see your books.
Everyone get back to work.

146
00:16:37,880 --> 00:16:40,678
We're not being treated fairly.
I'm speaking to Lacy.

147
00:16:40,883 --> 00:16:41,850
Me too.

148
00:16:42,051 --> 00:16:43,575
Excuse me, Miss Warfield.

149
00:16:44,286 --> 00:16:47,722
I speak for us all when I say
we'll do our best to cooperate.

150
00:16:48,157 --> 00:16:49,522
Thank you.

151
00:16:49,725 --> 00:16:52,558
But a reporter's first allegiance
is to the truth.

152
00:16:52,828 --> 00:16:56,559
The people of this city depend on us
and we can't let them down.

153
00:16:57,566 --> 00:16:58,692
Thank you.

154
00:17:03,338 --> 00:17:04,896
Is he for real?

155
00:17:05,441 --> 00:17:09,434
100 percent, and I like him that way.

156
00:17:09,678 --> 00:17:11,236
Oh, you have a thing for him.

157
00:17:11,480 --> 00:17:14,142
For Clark?! No!

158
00:17:14,349 --> 00:17:16,249
He's kind of cute.

159
00:17:16,852 --> 00:17:19,218
Look, Miss Warfield...

160
00:17:19,421 --> 00:17:22,879
...Clark is the oldest
living boy scout, okay?

161
00:17:23,092 --> 00:17:25,390
He's trustworthy, he's helpful...

162
00:17:25,594 --> 00:17:28,256
...he's loyal, he's obedient, he...

163
00:17:28,864 --> 00:17:30,525
I don't know how to tell you this.

164
00:17:30,733 --> 00:17:35,432
I just don't think he'd be attracted
to somebody like you.

165
00:17:35,637 --> 00:17:40,301
Don't be silly. All men like me.
I'm very, very rich!

166
00:17:41,210 --> 00:17:45,146
Why are there no air travel expenses
for you, Mr. Kent?

167
00:17:45,347 --> 00:17:47,815
I get airsick, especially
when it's bumpy.

168
00:17:48,417 --> 00:17:50,248
Lois, get in here!

169
00:17:52,521 --> 00:17:55,115
Lois, explain this column of figures.

170
00:17:55,724 --> 00:17:58,955
- The president is coming on live.
- What, right now?

171
00:17:59,328 --> 00:18:02,024
- It won't be very good news.
- You always overreact.

172
00:18:02,231 --> 00:18:06,497
- It won't be that terrible.
- Hopefully very terrible, Miss Lane.

173
00:18:06,702 --> 00:18:09,728
We can double our circulation
with an international crisis.

174
00:18:09,972 --> 00:18:12,600
<i>And because the summit has failed...</i>

175
00:18:14,076 --> 00:18:17,944
<i>... we have no choice but</i>
<i>to strive to be second to none...</i>

176
00:18:18,147 --> 00:18:20,047
<i>... in the nuclear arms race.</i>

177
00:18:20,249 --> 00:18:24,845
<i>Therefore, I am announcing</i>
<i>the following measures...</i>

178
00:18:27,723 --> 00:18:30,521
I know you're all upset
by the crisis.

179
00:18:31,193 --> 00:18:35,129
The best thing we can do
is to try to think positively.

180
00:18:35,898 --> 00:18:40,301
Now, is there anything we can do?
Doesn't anyone have a suggestion?

181
00:18:41,370 --> 00:18:45,466
All right, I'll make a suggestion.

182
00:18:46,975 --> 00:18:49,341
Why don't we write to our congressman?

183
00:18:49,545 --> 00:18:53,345
- That'll do a lot of good.
- Somebody has to be an optimist.

184
00:18:54,917 --> 00:18:56,179
Jeremy?

185
00:18:58,253 --> 00:19:02,189
- What could we do about the crisis?
- He doesn't know what's going on.

186
00:19:04,259 --> 00:19:07,194
I know who I'd write a letter to
that would do some good.

187
00:19:07,396 --> 00:19:10,797
- Who? Santa Claus?
- No, Superman!

188
00:19:10,999 --> 00:19:13,126
Superman, the subject
of our exhibit...

189
00:19:13,335 --> 00:19:16,634
...has donated a strand
of his hair to the museum...

190
00:19:16,839 --> 00:19:19,831
...so we can have the fun
of seeing how strong he really is.

191
00:19:20,042 --> 00:19:22,203
Here you see a 1000-pound load...

192
00:19:22,444 --> 00:19:25,971
...easily suspended
by his single hair.

193
00:19:26,215 --> 00:19:30,345
The museum will be closing soon,
so we should hurry a little.

194
00:19:31,453 --> 00:19:34,616
Know what I can do with a single
strand of Superman's hair?

195
00:19:34,823 --> 00:19:37,121
You could make a toupee that flies.

196
00:19:38,026 --> 00:19:41,291
That hair is a sample
of Superman's genetic material.

197
00:19:41,496 --> 00:19:43,726
The building blocks of his body.

198
00:19:44,066 --> 00:19:48,332
With my genius and enough nuclear
power to mutate the genes...

199
00:19:48,537 --> 00:19:51,734
...I can create a being
who's more powerful than him.

200
00:19:53,242 --> 00:19:56,075
With total allegiance to me.

201
00:20:04,987 --> 00:20:07,751
You better stand back.
Keep your eye out.

202
00:20:38,954 --> 00:20:42,651
- Miss Warfield, you wanted to see me?
- Hi, Clark. Please come in.

203
00:20:43,225 --> 00:20:45,853
I've come up with a brilliant idea.

204
00:20:46,061 --> 00:20:47,528
Oh, really?

205
00:20:47,729 --> 00:20:49,458
Well, Daddy thinks it's brilliant.

206
00:20:49,665 --> 00:20:53,601
I want you to write a new series
called "Metropolis After Hours."

207
00:20:53,802 --> 00:20:55,463
Who, me? I...

208
00:20:55,671 --> 00:20:58,697
It's wonderful. It's great, isn't it?

209
00:20:59,207 --> 00:21:03,007
- I don't think I'd be right for this.
- Oh, you're perfect for it.

210
00:21:03,211 --> 00:21:06,874
I mean, you're young, you're single,
you're successful.

211
00:21:07,082 --> 00:21:08,743
I'm usually in bed by 10:30.

212
00:21:08,951 --> 00:21:11,647
That's just it, see, you don't
have to flaunt it.

213
00:21:11,853 --> 00:21:14,583
I mean, you're no slave to fashion.
Although...

214
00:21:14,790 --> 00:21:18,851
...have you ever thought of contacts?
- They make my eyes itch.

215
00:21:19,061 --> 00:21:22,428
Don't worry about it. I thought
we could do this together.

216
00:21:22,631 --> 00:21:24,963
- Oh?
- I know all the right places.

217
00:21:25,167 --> 00:21:27,067
I'm a member of all the right clubs.

218
00:21:27,269 --> 00:21:29,965
We'll start tonight at the opening
of the Metro Club.

219
00:21:30,172 --> 00:21:33,141
- Oh, tonight.
- Yeah, it's a date.

220
00:21:33,342 --> 00:21:34,309
A date!

221
00:21:34,543 --> 00:21:35,510
A date?

222
00:21:35,744 --> 00:21:38,406
Well, it's just business, actually.

223
00:21:39,047 --> 00:21:42,346
I've got a letter here for Superman,
care of me.

224
00:21:42,551 --> 00:21:44,610
- What?
- Superman gets mail here?

225
00:21:44,820 --> 00:21:47,687
It's probably a picture request.
I can take care of it.

226
00:21:47,889 --> 00:21:51,848
I think it's more than just
a fan letter. You should read it.

227
00:21:52,828 --> 00:21:57,390
"Dear Superman, my teacher spoke about
the president's speech on the arms race.

228
00:21:59,968 --> 00:22:02,232
We're all very unhappy about it.

229
00:22:03,171 --> 00:22:07,608
And I said we should get Superman
to rid the world of nuclear arms...

230
00:22:08,744 --> 00:22:10,507
...because only he could do it.

231
00:22:12,647 --> 00:22:17,380
Once you've destroyed all the nuclear
missiles, they'll see I'm right.

232
00:22:17,586 --> 00:22:21,113
Superman can make sure we don't
blow ourselves up, quick and easy.

233
00:22:21,323 --> 00:22:24,417
I know you'll come through.
Your friend, Jeremy."

234
00:22:24,626 --> 00:22:27,789
Poor kid. Oh, well,
I better get back to work.

235
00:22:27,996 --> 00:22:31,796
- No, there's an angle in this.
- An angle! He's just a kid!

236
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:36,767
Daddy loves whipping up campaigns.
Oh, boy, and the public loves it!

237
00:22:36,972 --> 00:22:38,439
Lacy!

238
00:22:39,207 --> 00:22:40,572
We'll make him a celebrity.

239
00:22:40,776 --> 00:22:44,837
Everybody in the world is gonna be
wondering what Superman's reply is.

240
00:22:48,383 --> 00:22:50,544
Welcome to Metropolis, Jeremy.

241
00:22:50,752 --> 00:22:54,313
I'm Mr. Warfield and this is
my daughter, Lacy Warfield.

242
00:22:54,523 --> 00:22:57,253
- Hi, Jeremy.
- Now come along and meet the press.

243
00:22:57,459 --> 00:22:59,927
- Don't you trip.
- The car had a flat.

244
00:23:00,128 --> 00:23:01,993
Sorry to hear that.
Turn around.

245
00:23:02,197 --> 00:23:04,461
Let everybody get a picture of you.

246
00:23:04,666 --> 00:23:06,827
- That's it, everyone.
- Here, Jeremy.

247
00:23:07,035 --> 00:23:09,560
What a boy! Now come along...

248
00:23:09,771 --> 00:23:12,934
...and tell the American public
what you told me.

249
00:23:13,175 --> 00:23:16,144
I just said I wish Superman
would've said yes.

250
00:23:16,378 --> 00:23:18,005
- Did you get that?
- No, we didn't.

251
00:23:18,246 --> 00:23:20,578
Well, say it again. Loudly.

252
00:23:20,782 --> 00:23:23,910
I just said I wish Superman
would've just said yes!

253
00:23:31,960 --> 00:23:33,052
Miss Lane!

254
00:23:33,395 --> 00:23:37,297
Miss Lane. Take a look at this.
Hot off the press.

255
00:23:37,532 --> 00:23:39,432
Oh, my God!

256
00:23:39,634 --> 00:23:43,126
This time he's gone too far.
Look, Clark. Look at that.

257
00:23:43,338 --> 00:23:45,431
Can't wait to see
the chief's reaction.

258
00:23:46,241 --> 00:23:48,573
I'm through taking it lying down.

259
00:23:49,311 --> 00:23:51,108
Anybody wants me, I'll be downtown.

260
00:23:51,513 --> 00:23:53,310
Chief look different to you?

261
00:23:53,682 --> 00:23:57,516
He looks like my father when he went
to the bank to ask for a loan.

262
00:23:58,019 --> 00:23:59,919
I'm gonna make sure he's all right.

263
00:24:00,455 --> 00:24:05,392
There's nothing we can do about it.
It's Superman's decision now.

264
00:24:05,794 --> 00:24:08,194
I'm sure he'll do the right thing.

265
00:24:45,967 --> 00:24:48,435
<i>May the elders watch over you...</i>

266
00:24:49,204 --> 00:24:50,501
<i>... my son.</i>

267
00:24:52,073 --> 00:24:55,600
<i>Their wisdom is all that is left</i>
<i>of a once powerful...</i>

268
00:24:55,844 --> 00:24:58,005
<i>... and enlightened planet.</i>

269
00:24:59,781 --> 00:25:03,410
<i>You must listen to them, Kal-El.</i>

270
00:25:04,853 --> 00:25:05,945
<i>Listen.</i>

271
00:25:11,359 --> 00:25:13,725
I know I'm forbidden to interfere.

272
00:25:14,462 --> 00:25:18,865
And yet the Earth is threatened
by the same fate as Krypton's.

273
00:25:19,067 --> 00:25:21,535
The Earth is too primitive.

274
00:25:21,736 --> 00:25:23,829
You can flee to new worlds...

275
00:25:24,306 --> 00:25:27,434
...where war is long forgotten.

276
00:25:28,076 --> 00:25:31,307
If you teach the Earth to put
its fate in any one man...

277
00:25:31,980 --> 00:25:35,780
...even yourself, you're teaching them
to be betrayed.

278
00:25:38,787 --> 00:25:41,278
Betrayed... betrayed...

279
00:25:41,489 --> 00:25:44,458
...betrayed... betrayed!

280
00:25:47,128 --> 00:25:50,655
<i>And because the summit has failed...</i>

281
00:25:50,865 --> 00:25:54,130
<i>... we have no choice but to strive...</i>

282
00:25:54,336 --> 00:25:59,273
<i>... to be second to none</i>
<i>in the nuclear arms race.</i>

283
00:25:59,708 --> 00:26:01,175
<i>To that end...</i>

284
00:26:01,409 --> 00:26:04,401
<i>... this administration has pursued...</i>

285
00:26:04,646 --> 00:26:07,444
<i>... and will continue to pursue...</i>

286
00:26:07,649 --> 00:26:09,776
<i>... the most vigorous policy.</i>

287
00:26:10,118 --> 00:26:11,517
<i>Therefore...</i>

288
00:26:15,123 --> 00:26:16,215
Just a minute.

289
00:26:20,295 --> 00:26:22,889
- Lois?
- There you are. What happened?

290
00:26:23,098 --> 00:26:25,931
- What do you mean, what happened?
- Nothing, just:

291
00:26:26,134 --> 00:26:28,602
"Meet in the lobby at 6 for
the awards dinner.

292
00:26:28,803 --> 00:26:30,998
Wear something nice
and don't be late."

293
00:26:31,206 --> 00:26:35,006
- Was it some other Lois?
- I'm sorry, I completely forgot.

294
00:26:35,243 --> 00:26:38,144
Okay, go get your penguin suit on
and we'll go.

295
00:26:38,647 --> 00:26:43,175
I'd rather not, if you don't mind.
I've got a lot of thinking to do.

296
00:26:43,385 --> 00:26:45,114
But you go ahead. Okay?

297
00:26:48,456 --> 00:26:49,480
Clark?

298
00:26:50,492 --> 00:26:52,323
Something's wrong, isn't it?

299
00:26:55,864 --> 00:27:00,096
- Is there anything I can do?
- Yes, you can, as a matter of fact.

300
00:27:00,302 --> 00:27:03,032
- What?
- Could we go get some fresh air?

301
00:27:05,340 --> 00:27:06,534
Fresh air?

302
00:27:07,008 --> 00:27:09,875
Fresh air. Fresh air, sure.

303
00:27:10,078 --> 00:27:11,909
Sure, Clark. Sure.

304
00:27:12,280 --> 00:27:14,714
Who needs chicken with
all the fixings anyway?

305
00:27:14,916 --> 00:27:17,476
Let's go. Come on.
Let's get some fresh air.

306
00:27:18,887 --> 00:27:20,912
Breathe. Do you feel better?

307
00:27:22,090 --> 00:27:23,057
Clark?

308
00:27:23,258 --> 00:27:26,022
Clark? Clark, things aren't
that bad! Stop!

309
00:27:26,227 --> 00:27:27,421
Oh, Clark!

310
00:27:28,196 --> 00:27:29,891
Clark! Clark!

311
00:27:39,407 --> 00:27:40,874
Superman!

312
00:28:01,129 --> 00:28:02,323
You okay?

313
00:28:02,764 --> 00:28:03,856
Great.

314
00:28:13,575 --> 00:28:15,702
Hey, look at that.

315
00:28:27,188 --> 00:28:28,951
There you go. Bye-bye!

316
00:28:59,421 --> 00:29:02,390
- How'd you like going solo?
- I loved it.

317
00:29:02,590 --> 00:29:04,558
But not as much as being with you.

318
00:29:04,759 --> 00:29:07,626
I needed to be with you too.
You make me laugh.

319
00:29:11,599 --> 00:29:13,829
You're the only one
I can talk to, Lois.

320
00:29:14,202 --> 00:29:18,662
See, sometimes I don't know
what I'm supposed to do.

321
00:29:20,708 --> 00:29:23,506
I'm always here for you, you know that.

322
00:29:24,112 --> 00:29:27,707
And you'll do the right thing,
no matter what. You always have.

323
00:29:28,249 --> 00:29:29,375
Thank you.

324
00:29:30,585 --> 00:29:32,382
- You know something?
- What?

325
00:29:32,887 --> 00:29:36,653
- You don't even know my name.
- Kal-El.

326
00:29:39,060 --> 00:29:40,652
You remember, don't you?

327
00:29:41,996 --> 00:29:43,623
I remember everything.

328
00:29:43,865 --> 00:29:48,802
"Never set one of them above the rest.
Love all humanity instead."

329
00:29:52,207 --> 00:29:53,504
That's not fair.

330
00:30:20,368 --> 00:30:21,198
Lois.

331
00:30:21,803 --> 00:30:24,363
Lois, it's time to go. We'll be late.

332
00:30:27,242 --> 00:30:30,040
What am I doing out here
freezing my butt off?

333
00:30:30,245 --> 00:30:33,043
Oh, you wanted some fresh air.

334
00:30:33,815 --> 00:30:37,182
Oh, no that's okay.
I don't want to catch a cold.

335
00:30:37,385 --> 00:30:41,754
I feel kind of weird,
like I'm jetlagged or something.

336
00:30:41,956 --> 00:30:43,924
- Jeepers!
- Like I'm going crazy.

337
00:30:45,727 --> 00:30:50,096
- How about you? Are you still down?
- Nope. Things are pretty clear.

338
00:30:50,632 --> 00:30:54,432
Good. Too much thinking
wears down your batteries.

339
00:30:56,170 --> 00:31:00,402
Clark, you gotta go with your gut.

340
00:31:00,909 --> 00:31:02,035
Come on.

341
00:31:07,015 --> 00:31:08,505
Okay, here you go, Jeremy.

342
00:31:09,050 --> 00:31:12,417
Mr. Warfield wants me to get shots
of you with local color...

343
00:31:12,620 --> 00:31:14,383
...but I can't think of anything.

344
00:31:16,057 --> 00:31:18,048
- Hi, Jeremy.
- Superman!

345
00:31:18,893 --> 00:31:19,951
Jimmy.

346
00:31:20,562 --> 00:31:21,893
What a scoop!

347
00:31:23,431 --> 00:31:25,558
- How'd you like to take a walk?
- Sure!

348
00:31:25,767 --> 00:31:27,359
Jimmy, come on.

349
00:31:41,583 --> 00:31:43,483
You can't! You'll get towed.

350
00:31:44,819 --> 00:31:47,151
Do you know how much
a ticket costs?

351
00:31:47,355 --> 00:31:48,913
Lacy, it's only money.

352
00:31:57,799 --> 00:32:00,393
Will you wait for me
upstairs in the gallery?

353
00:32:00,602 --> 00:32:01,591
Sure, okay.

354
00:32:01,803 --> 00:32:03,964
- Good luck, Superman.
- Thanks.

355
00:32:13,181 --> 00:32:14,478
I saved you a seat.

356
00:32:20,121 --> 00:32:21,281
All right, Superman!

357
00:32:24,359 --> 00:32:27,817
I don't represent any country but
I'd like to address the delegates.

358
00:32:28,029 --> 00:32:32,022
Well, in that case,
you will need a sponsor.

359
00:32:34,535 --> 00:32:37,163
I believe that will do. Please.

360
00:32:41,175 --> 00:32:42,233
Thank you.

361
00:32:44,545 --> 00:32:45,978
What's he gonna say?

362
00:32:46,681 --> 00:32:48,512
Something wonderful.

363
00:32:49,651 --> 00:32:51,175
Madam Secretary...

364
00:32:51,786 --> 00:32:55,244
...honorable delegates,
ladies and gentlemen.

365
00:32:55,456 --> 00:32:58,516
For many years now
I've lived among you as...

366
00:32:58,726 --> 00:33:02,560
...a visitor. I've seen
the beauty of your many cultures.

367
00:33:03,231 --> 00:33:05,927
I've felt joy in your magnificent
accomplishments.

368
00:33:06,868 --> 00:33:09,234
I've also seen the folly of your wars.

369
00:33:10,672 --> 00:33:14,108
As of today I'm not a visitor
anymore, because the Earth...

370
00:33:15,076 --> 00:33:16,703
...is my home too.

371
00:33:17,645 --> 00:33:20,307
We can't live in fear.
And I can't stand...

372
00:33:20,515 --> 00:33:24,042
...idly by and watch us
stumble into the madness...

373
00:33:24,252 --> 00:33:26,243
...of possible nuclear destruction.

374
00:33:26,854 --> 00:33:28,253
I've come to a decision.

375
00:33:29,257 --> 00:33:32,590
I'm going to do what our governments
have been unwilling to do.

376
00:33:33,227 --> 00:33:37,994
Effective immediately, I'm going to
rid our planet of all nuclear weapons.

377
00:33:39,867 --> 00:33:41,630
All right, Superman!

378
00:33:44,739 --> 00:33:46,707
Way to go, Superman!

379
00:34:03,524 --> 00:34:05,651
Missile test Alpha, all systems go.

380
00:34:05,860 --> 00:34:08,488
<i>- three... two... one.</i>

381
00:35:57,605 --> 00:35:58,697
Oh!

382
00:35:58,940 --> 00:36:01,465
Oh. Nice to see you guys!

383
00:36:03,511 --> 00:36:07,811
Why don't you just relax there.
I'll get on with the introductions:

384
00:36:08,015 --> 00:36:09,107
Dixie.

385
00:36:09,884 --> 00:36:11,146
And Trixie.

386
00:36:13,888 --> 00:36:18,518
From the land of the free, the home of
the great cost overrun, Harry Howler:

387
00:36:18,993 --> 00:36:22,292
Nuclear strategist from
America's top think tank.

388
00:36:22,496 --> 00:36:25,056
And a great little warmonger
in his own right.

389
00:36:25,266 --> 00:36:27,757
A hearty <i>bienvenue</i>
to Jean-Pierre Dubois:

390
00:36:28,636 --> 00:36:31,264
Nuclear warhead dealer to the world.

391
00:36:31,772 --> 00:36:33,296
His motto is:

392
00:36:33,774 --> 00:36:36,038
"If you didn't buy it
from Jean-Pierre...

393
00:36:36,277 --> 00:36:38,404
...you didn't buy it
on the black market."

394
00:36:39,513 --> 00:36:40,980
General Romoff.

395
00:36:41,816 --> 00:36:44,580
A lot of people think of you
as the "Mad Russian."

396
00:36:45,553 --> 00:36:49,455
I like to think of you
as just madly eccentric.

397
00:36:49,657 --> 00:36:51,124
Please be seated.

398
00:36:53,394 --> 00:36:57,296
Look guys. I know you're all choked
up, kind of overcome with joy...

399
00:36:57,498 --> 00:37:00,262
...that Superman has ended
the arms race.

400
00:37:01,802 --> 00:37:05,397
But if we work together,
we can make the world safe...

401
00:37:05,640 --> 00:37:06,937
...for war profits.

402
00:37:07,375 --> 00:37:08,433
Get to the point.

403
00:37:08,776 --> 00:37:12,371
The point is, I, Lex Luthor, greatest
criminal mind of the modern era...

404
00:37:12,613 --> 00:37:14,877
...have found a way
to destroy Superman.

405
00:37:15,116 --> 00:37:17,744
Behold, my unscrupulous friends...

406
00:37:20,254 --> 00:37:21,585
Shut those blinds.

407
00:37:21,789 --> 00:37:25,384
- The sun is hurting my eyes!
- Exactly.

408
00:37:25,726 --> 00:37:27,318
You know what the sun is?

409
00:37:27,528 --> 00:37:30,326
It's nothing more than
a huge nuclear bomb...

410
00:37:30,531 --> 00:37:35,161
...a bomb with so much radiation, it'd
incinerate the average man like that!

411
00:37:35,870 --> 00:37:38,964
Yes, but Superman is no average man.

412
00:37:39,273 --> 00:37:40,934
Aha, right!

413
00:37:42,343 --> 00:37:43,810
What is your plan?

414
00:37:44,478 --> 00:37:48,380
Boys, old Lex here
has kind of a secret recipe...

415
00:37:48,582 --> 00:37:52,348
...a genetic stew in this dish,
if you will.

416
00:37:52,987 --> 00:37:55,820
If you'll help me put this
on one of your missiles...

417
00:37:56,023 --> 00:38:00,653
...I promise you, Superman will have
the biggest surprise of his life.

418
00:38:01,262 --> 00:38:05,289
I'll introduce him to his first
nightmare, a "Nuclear Man."

419
00:38:05,499 --> 00:38:09,868
He'll pierce his skin. He'll make
him mortal. He'll become sick.

420
00:38:10,071 --> 00:38:12,005
We'll dance on his grave.

421
00:38:12,540 --> 00:38:15,976
Why should we deal with
a notorious scoundrel like you?

422
00:38:16,210 --> 00:38:17,370
Remember my motto:

423
00:38:17,611 --> 00:38:20,444
"The more fear you make,
the more loot you take."

424
00:38:20,648 --> 00:38:22,707
And the more missiles you guys sell...

425
00:38:22,917 --> 00:38:26,375
Yes, but what's in it for you?

426
00:38:28,589 --> 00:38:30,454
A tiny commission.

427
00:38:31,359 --> 00:38:32,883
Something appropriate.

428
00:38:34,795 --> 00:38:36,092
A number...

429
00:38:36,630 --> 00:38:38,996
...with a lot of zeros behind it.

430
00:38:46,440 --> 00:38:47,600
Lenny.

431
00:38:48,309 --> 00:38:50,038
The new genetic material.

432
00:38:52,847 --> 00:38:54,337
And now, Leonard...

433
00:38:55,082 --> 00:38:56,674
...your Uncle Lex...

434
00:38:56,884 --> 00:39:01,378
...with this protoplasm that I have
grown from Superman's hair cells...

435
00:39:02,690 --> 00:39:05,523
...will duplicate creation itself.

436
00:39:07,194 --> 00:39:08,593
Now the fabric.

437
00:39:10,931 --> 00:39:13,422
Uncle Lex, this ain't gonna cover him.

438
00:39:15,703 --> 00:39:18,263
The computer inside will...

439
00:39:19,240 --> 00:39:22,835
...leave enough material to maintain
the high moral standards...

440
00:39:23,077 --> 00:39:26,478
...that I've always subscribed to.

441
00:39:26,680 --> 00:39:28,545
Know what this means, Uncle Lex?

442
00:39:28,949 --> 00:39:30,007
What?

443
00:39:30,217 --> 00:39:31,775
We're gonna be parents.

444
00:40:02,316 --> 00:40:04,648
- What's your name, sergeant?
- York, sir.

445
00:40:04,852 --> 00:40:06,046
At ease.

446
00:40:38,085 --> 00:40:40,110
Launch control. Yes, sir.

447
00:40:40,321 --> 00:40:42,084
Yes, sir.

448
00:40:42,656 --> 00:40:45,216
There's a weather problem.
We gotta hold.

449
00:40:45,793 --> 00:40:46,987
Hold?

450
00:40:47,495 --> 00:40:49,463
- What's your name, son?
- Goram.

451
00:40:49,663 --> 00:40:50,960
"Goram, sir."

452
00:40:51,165 --> 00:40:53,531
- Goram, sir.
- Goram, you know your code book?

453
00:40:53,734 --> 00:40:55,031
Of course, sir.

454
00:40:55,236 --> 00:40:59,400
27-0-6, inclement override.
Fire on my command. Fire.

455
00:40:59,640 --> 00:41:02,200
Yes, sir. Stand by to launch.

456
00:41:04,211 --> 00:41:05,872
Ten... nine...

457
00:41:19,326 --> 00:41:20,258
Missed us.

458
00:42:38,572 --> 00:42:40,199
Reach out.

459
00:42:40,808 --> 00:42:42,298
Come on.

460
00:42:43,177 --> 00:42:44,610
Down.

461
00:42:45,112 --> 00:42:46,477
Reach out.

462
00:42:46,680 --> 00:42:48,944
And stretch.

463
00:42:49,149 --> 00:42:50,411
Down.

464
00:42:50,884 --> 00:42:52,181
Up.

465
00:42:52,586 --> 00:42:55,680
- Clark, are you okay?
- I think I better sit this one out.

466
00:42:55,889 --> 00:42:59,791
You sure? This would be great for
your series on the young Metropolis.

467
00:42:59,994 --> 00:43:01,894
Let's try it again. Come on.

468
00:43:02,096 --> 00:43:04,826
Two, three, four.

469
00:43:05,032 --> 00:43:07,967
One, two, three.

470
00:43:08,202 --> 00:43:11,399
- I don't think so.
- What, are you okay?

471
00:43:19,780 --> 00:43:21,111
28.

472
00:43:21,315 --> 00:43:22,373
29.

473
00:43:22,616 --> 00:43:23,913
23.

474
00:43:24,318 --> 00:43:27,219
- Done. Great.
- Okay, you try it now.

475
00:43:27,721 --> 00:43:31,714
- Let's set it a little higher for you.
- Okay.

476
00:43:32,059 --> 00:43:33,651
Just push down.

477
00:43:37,598 --> 00:43:41,193
- Are you okay? Just step down.
- Need some help?

478
00:43:42,770 --> 00:43:44,965
Your friend doesn't know
his own strength.

479
00:43:45,172 --> 00:43:46,799
Clark, this is Paul.

480
00:43:47,041 --> 00:43:48,872
- He's a trainer here.
- Hi.

481
00:43:49,109 --> 00:43:51,339
Hey, I got just the thing for you.

482
00:43:51,712 --> 00:43:53,441
Over here, Clarky.

483
00:43:53,847 --> 00:43:55,041
Clarky?

484
00:43:59,386 --> 00:44:01,581
It's real nice of him to help me out.

485
00:44:01,955 --> 00:44:04,287
- He's really good.
- Here, try this one.

486
00:44:04,491 --> 00:44:07,688
Clark! Are you okay? Sorry.

487
00:44:07,895 --> 00:44:09,590
No pain, no gain.

488
00:44:11,398 --> 00:44:13,628
Jeez, what a jerk.

489
00:44:14,268 --> 00:44:16,429
Never realized it before.

490
00:44:16,970 --> 00:44:19,336
I guess a lot of people
I know are jerks.

491
00:44:19,573 --> 00:44:22,974
