501
00:44:56,076 --> 00:44:57,236
No pain, no gain?

502
00:45:07,521 --> 00:45:08,249
What was that?

503
00:45:11,558 --> 00:45:15,119
Uncle Lex...
You're spooking me out.

504
00:45:17,464 --> 00:45:18,590
There.

505
00:45:20,834 --> 00:45:23,826
Madam, thank you very much.

506
00:45:48,128 --> 00:45:49,425
I'm incredible.

507
00:45:52,032 --> 00:45:53,431
Uncle Lex, he's like...

508
00:45:55,436 --> 00:45:57,370
He's beautiful. He's perfect.

509
00:45:59,106 --> 00:46:01,074
Welcome home, Nuclear Man.

510
00:46:01,575 --> 00:46:03,839
Your father's happy to see you.

511
00:46:19,426 --> 00:46:22,953
The power of the sun has given him
internally generated heat.

512
00:46:26,200 --> 00:46:27,497
I'm a...

513
00:46:28,101 --> 00:46:29,534
You are...

514
00:46:30,637 --> 00:46:34,164
I'm... What? I'm a genius?

515
00:46:34,408 --> 00:46:36,376
I'm incredible. I'm...

516
00:46:36,977 --> 00:46:38,945
You are nothing.

517
00:46:39,513 --> 00:46:41,174
I am the father now.

518
00:46:41,448 --> 00:46:42,415
You have my voice.

519
00:46:42,916 --> 00:46:45,680
No, you have my voice.

520
00:46:46,720 --> 00:46:48,244
Just remember, I made you.

521
00:46:48,622 --> 00:46:51,523
Yeah, you're just an experiment,
freako.

522
00:46:53,994 --> 00:46:55,188
What is that?

523
00:46:55,762 --> 00:46:59,755
- Oh, no.
- I'm an experiment. I'm a freako.

524
00:47:00,601 --> 00:47:03,069
I was just kidding about
that freako line!

525
00:47:03,270 --> 00:47:06,330
If anybody's a freako around here,
it's gotta be me!

526
00:47:09,042 --> 00:47:11,237
Oh, wow, I'm break dancing, hey!

527
00:47:11,478 --> 00:47:13,343
This rocks. Hey!

528
00:47:16,283 --> 00:47:17,910
I made you. I can destroy you.

529
00:47:18,285 --> 00:47:19,809
Destroy.

530
00:47:20,320 --> 00:47:22,379
Destroy Superman now.

531
00:47:22,789 --> 00:47:26,088
You sweet thing.
But not quite yet, no.

532
00:47:27,027 --> 00:47:30,758
Come here. We'll discuss
when the proper time is.

533
00:47:37,471 --> 00:47:38,733
Uncle Lex.

534
00:47:45,379 --> 00:47:46,744
Oh, no!

535
00:47:47,014 --> 00:47:49,949
He's, like... He's, like, cold.

536
00:47:50,150 --> 00:47:51,640
Of course he is.

537
00:47:52,619 --> 00:47:56,419
That's his vulnerability. That's
the only way he can be stopped.

538
00:47:56,623 --> 00:47:57,749
What?

539
00:47:58,892 --> 00:48:03,329
Lenny, my loud-mouthed nephew,
he gets his energy from the sun.

540
00:48:03,630 --> 00:48:05,860
Without it, he's like you at night:

541
00:48:06,500 --> 00:48:07,330
Useless.

542
00:48:21,915 --> 00:48:23,143
Well, nobody's perfect.

543
00:48:29,690 --> 00:48:33,649
I never had a double date before.
This is fun. How do I look?

544
00:48:34,962 --> 00:48:39,160
Illegal. Like the last six dresses
you tried on.

545
00:48:39,366 --> 00:48:43,598
Listen, Lacy? I don't want to
burst your bubble or anything but...

546
00:48:43,804 --> 00:48:46,136
...Clark's not gonna notice
what you're wearing.

547
00:48:46,373 --> 00:48:48,102
Yes, he will. There's Clark.

548
00:48:48,342 --> 00:48:51,038
Okay, fix that. There you go.
You look great.

549
00:48:51,278 --> 00:48:54,270
- Maybe it's just Superman.
- No.

550
00:48:54,881 --> 00:48:58,977
No, Superman makes a different
kind of entrance.

551
00:49:10,163 --> 00:49:11,858
- Hi, Lacy.
- Hi, Clark.

552
00:49:12,065 --> 00:49:14,625
Can you break a 20?
Driver didn't have any change.

553
00:49:15,102 --> 00:49:17,400
Yeah, sure. Let me get my purse.

554
00:49:17,604 --> 00:49:19,538
- Hi, Lois.
- Hi, Clark.

555
00:49:19,873 --> 00:49:20,669
- Clark.
- What?

556
00:49:20,907 --> 00:49:23,467
You are not gonna believe
this list of questions...

557
00:49:23,710 --> 00:49:26,235
...Mr. Warfield gave me
to ask Superman. Look.

558
00:49:26,980 --> 00:49:30,507
"Aren't you part of a plot
to weaken our national defense?"

559
00:49:30,717 --> 00:49:33,208
- Oh, my goodness.
- I think his gray matter is...

560
00:49:33,420 --> 00:49:36,856
- How will I ask him these questions?
- Well, politely I guess.

561
00:49:37,057 --> 00:49:40,686
Let's see, I have 18 dollars and...

562
00:49:41,028 --> 00:49:44,794
Clark, she really likes you,
so notice the dress.

563
00:49:45,232 --> 00:49:46,824
...my American Express card.

564
00:49:47,034 --> 00:49:49,434
- Dress.
- Oh, hey, neat dress.

565
00:49:49,970 --> 00:49:51,665
Well, thanks. Be right back.

566
00:49:55,509 --> 00:49:56,874
What's that?

567
00:49:59,146 --> 00:50:01,614
Now, there's a different
kind of entrance.

568
00:50:05,552 --> 00:50:06,917
- Hi, Lois.
- Hello, Superman.

569
00:50:07,120 --> 00:50:08,382
How are you?

570
00:50:08,855 --> 00:50:10,152
I'm fine.

571
00:50:11,324 --> 00:50:15,488
Oh, Superman, this is Lacy Warfield.
She's the boss' daughter.

572
00:50:15,696 --> 00:50:18,062
How do you do?
That's a very attractive outfit.

573
00:50:18,265 --> 00:50:21,701
- I think we better start our interview.
- Excuse me.

574
00:50:21,902 --> 00:50:23,392
Two's company.

575
00:50:23,970 --> 00:50:26,871
Oh, right, yeah.
Yeah, I'll go get Clark.

576
00:50:28,475 --> 00:50:33,276
He's probably helping the driver
change a tire, or some other good deed.

577
00:50:33,480 --> 00:50:34,310
That guy.

578
00:50:35,849 --> 00:50:38,477
- Something smells wonderful.
- Oh, thank you.

579
00:50:38,685 --> 00:50:41,279
I'm cooking some scallops
and some duck...

580
00:50:41,488 --> 00:50:44,980
...in this wonderful mushroom sauce
with champagne.

581
00:50:45,192 --> 00:50:47,524
In case we got hungry afterwards.

582
00:50:47,961 --> 00:50:49,588
I mean, later.

583
00:50:50,330 --> 00:50:52,491
You shouldn't have gone
to all that trouble.

584
00:50:59,005 --> 00:51:01,235
Should we get on with the interview?

585
00:51:01,475 --> 00:51:04,569
Yes, let's. Let's get on
with the interview.

586
00:51:08,415 --> 00:51:13,352
Have you had any trouble
confiscating the missiles?

587
00:51:13,787 --> 00:51:16,813
There always was the possibility
that warped individuals...

588
00:51:17,023 --> 00:51:19,856
...would take advantage of
the world's goodwill, but...

589
00:51:21,728 --> 00:51:23,195
Is there something wrong?

590
00:51:26,867 --> 00:51:29,734
Oh! My dinner! My dinner!

591
00:51:29,936 --> 00:51:31,665
I'll be right back.

592
00:51:32,172 --> 00:51:33,469
Be right back.

593
00:51:46,186 --> 00:51:47,016
Hi.

594
00:51:47,220 --> 00:51:50,189
- I missed you, Clark.
- Oh. Ah, well...

595
00:51:50,390 --> 00:51:54,190
It's so boring with Lois and Superman.
Let's do something wild.

596
00:51:54,394 --> 00:51:57,022
Gee, they're expecting us.
It wouldn't be polite.

597
00:51:57,230 --> 00:51:58,754
Yeah, you're right.

598
00:51:59,633 --> 00:52:03,000
How can one man be so square
and so delicious?

599
00:52:04,304 --> 00:52:08,434
All right, let's go chitchat. If I
have to face Superman, so do you.

600
00:52:09,409 --> 00:52:10,376
Lacy?

601
00:52:12,412 --> 00:52:13,970
Oh, Clark.

602
00:52:15,081 --> 00:52:16,105
Stop!

603
00:52:35,402 --> 00:52:40,135
I don't believe it! I never had duck
turn out so perfectly. It's amazing!

604
00:52:40,373 --> 00:52:41,340
I'm out here, Lois.

605
00:52:41,741 --> 00:52:42,799
Oh.

606
00:52:56,423 --> 00:52:59,722
- Isn't it beautiful?
- Yes, it is beautiful.

607
00:53:00,827 --> 00:53:02,624
The whole world is beautiful.

608
00:53:03,697 --> 00:53:08,293
I've always felt moments like this
should be shared with someone you...

609
00:53:09,769 --> 00:53:11,703
Someone you care a lot about.

610
00:53:14,174 --> 00:53:15,732
Isn't that the doorbell?

611
00:53:16,643 --> 00:53:17,667
Yes.

612
00:53:34,361 --> 00:53:35,623
Lacy!

613
00:53:37,230 --> 00:53:38,060
Where's Clark?

614
00:53:38,265 --> 00:53:40,426
He started to get in the elevator...

615
00:53:40,634 --> 00:53:42,932
Oh, never mind, it's a long story.

616
00:53:43,136 --> 00:53:45,229
It always is with Clark.

617
00:53:46,339 --> 00:53:47,897
Oh, great, that's him.

618
00:53:50,543 --> 00:53:51,771
- Clark?
- Hi.

619
00:53:52,012 --> 00:53:54,446
Those bellboys ought to
look where they're going.

620
00:53:54,648 --> 00:53:56,206
Superman?

621
00:53:56,516 --> 00:53:59,815
- I'm so glad you're back.
- Is dinner ready? Can we eat?

622
00:54:00,020 --> 00:54:02,318
- Yeah, let's go sit down.
- Oh, great.

623
00:54:06,993 --> 00:54:09,052
- Sorry!
- My goodness! No, that's okay.

624
00:54:09,262 --> 00:54:12,322
Just leave it there, Clark.
It's stuck on your pants.

625
00:54:12,532 --> 00:54:15,899
Yeah, let me just get a rag.
Excuse me, be right back.

626
00:54:20,273 --> 00:54:21,297
Where's Clark?

627
00:54:23,877 --> 00:54:27,745
<i>Hello, Dolly</i>
<i>Hello, Dolly</i>

628
00:54:27,948 --> 00:54:31,941
<i>It's so nice to have me back</i>
<i>Where I belong</i>

629
00:54:33,086 --> 00:54:36,419
<i>Don't be concerned, Blue Boy.</i>
<i>You're the only one who can hear me.</i>

630
00:54:36,623 --> 00:54:39,888
<i>It's my own private frequency.</i>
<i>You might call it "Lex TV."</i>

631
00:54:40,493 --> 00:54:43,257
<i>Look to your left,</i>
<i>tall, dark and handsome.</i>

632
00:54:44,164 --> 00:54:48,965
<i>I'm gonna blow 20 stories off that</i>
<i>building, give or take a floor or two.</i>

633
00:54:49,169 --> 00:54:50,261
<i>Peace.</i>

634
00:54:51,838 --> 00:54:52,930
Men.

635
00:54:53,173 --> 00:54:55,164
I hope Clark's okay. I better look.

636
00:54:55,408 --> 00:54:56,568
Okay.

637
00:54:59,746 --> 00:55:03,978
I'm sorry, but an emergency's come up.
My apologies to Miss Warfield.

638
00:55:04,184 --> 00:55:05,378
Oh, but...

639
00:55:05,652 --> 00:55:09,418
Superman! Take me with you!
I can cover the story!

640
00:55:11,424 --> 00:55:12,914
You seen Clark?

641
00:55:22,635 --> 00:55:25,866
Guess who. It's your old friend Lex.

642
00:55:26,973 --> 00:55:31,501
I suspect if you'd actually planted
a bomb, you'd be miles away by now.

643
00:55:32,412 --> 00:55:34,175
This is my nephew Lenny.

644
00:55:34,381 --> 00:55:35,609
He worships me.

645
00:55:35,815 --> 00:55:40,081
The dude of steel.
Boy, are you gonna get it!

646
00:55:41,554 --> 00:55:45,786
Silly me, thinking that
I could fool a super guy.

647
00:55:45,992 --> 00:55:48,426
You're right. No bomb.

648
00:55:48,628 --> 00:55:52,120
It's just that you're so involved
in this world peace bit...

649
00:55:52,332 --> 00:55:54,732
...you don't have time
for social calls.

650
00:55:55,168 --> 00:55:57,966
I confess, I tricked you.

651
00:55:58,371 --> 00:55:59,303
You look great.

652
00:55:59,506 --> 00:56:02,907
Never mind the small talk.
What are you up to?

653
00:56:04,044 --> 00:56:05,773
You know you're a workaholic?

654
00:56:05,979 --> 00:56:08,812
You're playing a good guy
24 hours a day.

655
00:56:09,015 --> 00:56:11,176
Why don't you stop and
smell the roses?

656
00:56:11,384 --> 00:56:14,581
Get yourself a hobby? A pet?
A kitten, a puppy?

657
00:56:14,788 --> 00:56:19,157
I know you hate children and animals.
What are you doing back in Metropolis?

658
00:56:19,359 --> 00:56:23,819
I want to be first to introduce
you to the new kid on the block.

659
00:56:37,477 --> 00:56:39,809
Look closely at the cell structure.

660
00:56:40,313 --> 00:56:42,281
You see anything familiar?

661
00:56:43,550 --> 00:56:45,745
You've already broken
all the laws of man.

662
00:56:45,952 --> 00:56:48,648
Now you've broken the laws
of nature too.

663
00:56:48,855 --> 00:56:51,187
I can only assume you hid a device...

664
00:56:51,391 --> 00:56:53,689
...in a missile I hurled into the sun.

665
00:56:54,027 --> 00:56:57,827
Mr. Muscle, I'm gonna really miss
these little chats we have together.

666
00:56:58,031 --> 00:57:00,261
You're the only one who can
keep up with me.

667
00:57:00,667 --> 00:57:02,862
- Lenny!
- What?

668
00:57:03,837 --> 00:57:05,930
I wanna propose a toast.

669
00:57:06,372 --> 00:57:10,775
To a nice guy, who's about
to finish last.

670
00:57:14,147 --> 00:57:15,739
Destroy Superman!

671
00:57:16,249 --> 00:57:17,375
Later.

672
00:57:18,118 --> 00:57:21,110
He's a little bit anxious.
Can you blame him?

673
00:57:22,455 --> 00:57:24,514
Not one of your great thinkers.

674
00:57:24,724 --> 00:57:27,852
But I, in all modesty, am.

675
00:57:28,061 --> 00:57:32,395
The touching thing about this plan
is you helped me devise it.

676
00:57:32,599 --> 00:57:35,796
Prison has twisted
your mind into a delusional state.

677
00:57:36,002 --> 00:57:38,095
No, no, no. Listen.

678
00:57:38,304 --> 00:57:41,432
When I escaped from prison
I had one thing on my mind:

679
00:57:41,674 --> 00:57:43,403
The end of Superman.

680
00:57:43,910 --> 00:57:46,276
So there I was,
the first time in my life...

681
00:57:46,479 --> 00:57:51,178
...that I didn't have a long-range,
truly devious, criminal scheme.

682
00:57:51,384 --> 00:57:53,443
And then I came up with it.

683
00:57:54,087 --> 00:57:55,452
With this guy...

684
00:57:55,755 --> 00:57:57,279
...and you gone...

685
00:57:57,524 --> 00:58:00,015
...I'll make a fortune
rearming the world.

686
00:58:00,226 --> 00:58:03,821
You'd risk global nuclear war for
your own personal financial gain.

687
00:58:04,030 --> 00:58:08,262
Nobody wants war. I just want
to keep the threat alive.

688
00:58:11,204 --> 00:58:12,603
Nifty, huh?

689
00:58:17,410 --> 00:58:19,037
Good night, sweet prince.

690
00:58:21,214 --> 00:58:22,772
Parting is...

691
00:58:23,349 --> 00:58:24,577
...inevitable.

692
00:58:25,652 --> 00:58:27,711
Destroy Superman!

693
00:58:28,021 --> 00:58:30,455
First, I have fun.

694
00:59:34,354 --> 00:59:35,446
Help me!

695
00:59:45,231 --> 00:59:46,425
Thanks, Superman!

696
01:05:22,068 --> 01:05:25,469
I said I'd get you to run
one of our papers yourself...

697
01:05:25,671 --> 01:05:27,605
...and I meant it.

698
01:05:28,307 --> 01:05:31,003
Congratulations, Miss Publisher.

699
01:05:31,243 --> 01:05:33,677
Thank you, Daddy, that's very nice.

700
01:05:33,879 --> 01:05:35,369
Step into your office.

701
01:05:38,284 --> 01:05:40,912
- Where'd this come from?
- Somebody brought it in.

702
01:05:41,120 --> 01:05:42,587
We bought it, cheap.

703
01:05:42,788 --> 01:05:45,723
Okay...
This time you've gone too far.

704
01:05:47,159 --> 01:05:50,128
You can print your stupid rag
without Lois Lane.

705
01:05:53,766 --> 01:05:57,167
And you certainly have
no right to this!

706
01:05:57,703 --> 01:06:00,638
- Lois, I'm sorry!
- Let her go, darling.

707
01:06:00,873 --> 01:06:02,568
I mean, she's useless.

708
01:06:02,875 --> 01:06:05,503
And while you're at it,
fire that Clark Kent.

709
01:06:05,745 --> 01:06:08,236
He hasn't been around.
He hasn't even telephoned.

710
01:06:08,481 --> 01:06:10,745
I know, I'm worried about him.

711
01:06:10,950 --> 01:06:12,577
Oh, kitten...

712
01:06:12,785 --> 01:06:17,279
...didn't we have a talk about
personal involvement with the help?

713
01:06:17,490 --> 01:06:20,254
- Now that you're the publisher...
- Daddy.

714
01:06:20,459 --> 01:06:22,518
- Yes, darling.
- Stuff it!

715
01:06:25,264 --> 01:06:28,028
Lois! Lois, I'm sorry.

716
01:06:28,234 --> 01:06:30,930
I promise you I had
nothing to do with that.

717
01:06:37,643 --> 01:06:39,201
Have you heard from Clark?

718
01:06:43,115 --> 01:06:44,343
No.

719
01:07:08,941 --> 01:07:10,306
Just a minute.

720
01:07:10,943 --> 01:07:12,308
Oh, Lois.

721
01:07:13,045 --> 01:07:15,377
- What are you doing here?
- I knew it.

722
01:07:16,182 --> 01:07:19,982
I just have a really bad flu.
What do you mean you knew it?

723
01:07:20,186 --> 01:07:21,448
How did you know?

724
01:07:23,956 --> 01:07:26,857
You haven't been to work.
You haven't called the office.

725
01:07:27,059 --> 01:07:30,495
You haven't even called me back.
How could you not call me back?

726
01:07:34,300 --> 01:07:37,633
Whatever it is,
I guess you've got your reasons.

727
01:07:39,271 --> 01:07:41,398
But I knew you were here, you know?

728
01:07:42,775 --> 01:07:44,003
Somehow...

729
01:07:44,677 --> 01:07:46,838
...something pulled me here.

730
01:07:47,113 --> 01:07:49,172
I always know when Superman's
in trouble.

731
01:07:49,415 --> 01:07:52,509
Superman?
Something's happened to him?

732
01:07:53,319 --> 01:07:55,981
Everybody's saying that
he's dead but...

733
01:07:56,756 --> 01:08:00,749
...that can't be true, I just know it.
I feel it in my heart.

734
01:08:01,060 --> 01:08:02,618
I think he just needs help.

735
01:08:03,729 --> 01:08:06,562
Wherever he is, Lois,
I'm sure he'll manage.

736
01:08:06,999 --> 01:08:10,526
Well, if he can't manage...

737
01:08:10,970 --> 01:08:14,599
...and if he really is in trouble...

738
01:08:14,840 --> 01:08:19,106
...then there's a few things
I'd like to tell him.

739
01:08:21,180 --> 01:08:22,647
I'd tell him...

740
01:08:23,716 --> 01:08:27,584
...that I will always cherish
the time we spent together.

741
01:08:28,154 --> 01:08:31,612
And that I never expected
anything in return.

742
01:08:32,458 --> 01:08:34,289
And no matter...

743
01:08:35,127 --> 01:08:38,494
...how few minutes I saw him for,
it always made me happy.

744
01:08:39,098 --> 01:08:42,363
And I would tell him
that I love him...

745
01:08:43,269 --> 01:08:45,237
...and that I'll always love him.

746
01:08:46,038 --> 01:08:47,130
And that...

747
01:08:47,773 --> 01:08:48,569
...whatever...

748
01:08:50,009 --> 01:08:52,477
...happens to the world...

749
01:08:53,212 --> 01:08:54,611
...I know that...

750
01:08:55,614 --> 01:08:59,710
...he's doing his best to make sure
it's all right for the rest of us.

751
01:09:00,119 --> 01:09:01,916
Well, wherever he is, Lois...

752
01:09:02,488 --> 01:09:06,322
...I know that he would
want to thank you.

753
01:09:13,532 --> 01:09:16,262
Listen, I'm pretty tired, you know?

754
01:09:16,468 --> 01:09:20,336
So I think I'll just rest here
for a while. Okay?

755
01:09:20,739 --> 01:09:22,138
I'll be fine.

756
01:09:22,741 --> 01:09:25,437
It's okay. Please?

757
01:09:28,948 --> 01:09:31,849
- I hope you feel better, Clark.
- Thanks.

758
01:09:41,227 --> 01:09:46,096
If you do see him, or hear from him...

759
01:09:48,701 --> 01:09:50,396
...he might need this.

760
01:09:58,010 --> 01:09:59,534
Oh, Lex.

761
01:09:59,778 --> 01:10:03,908
We're all very pleased at all
the nuclear missiles and arms...

762
01:10:04,116 --> 01:10:06,016
...you've helped us sell...

763
01:10:06,218 --> 01:10:10,120
...and we've decided
to increase your commission.

764
01:10:10,322 --> 01:10:13,314
Oh, guys, really, that's great.

765
01:10:14,093 --> 01:10:16,357
It is the least we could do.

766
01:10:16,896 --> 01:10:19,194
Well, I had another idea.
Gentlemen...

767
01:10:19,398 --> 01:10:23,198
...I've decided to assume
control of the company.

768
01:10:30,709 --> 01:10:33,041
My first official act,
of course, is to say:

769
01:10:33,245 --> 01:10:34,610
"You're fired!"

770
01:10:36,181 --> 01:10:37,409
You're mad!

771
01:10:37,616 --> 01:10:39,174
Oh, really?

772
01:10:49,061 --> 01:10:51,586
If you want a reference for work...

773
01:10:51,797 --> 01:10:53,321
...forget it!

774
01:10:56,735 --> 01:10:58,293
That's a good bit.

775
01:10:59,672 --> 01:11:03,665
You know with my brains, and your...
Frankly, your...

776
01:11:04,009 --> 01:11:07,501
...brawn, the possibilities
are absolutely staggering.

777
01:11:07,746 --> 01:11:10,806
You know, I could be president,
emperor, king.

778
01:11:11,250 --> 01:11:13,115
See how scared those guys were?

779
01:11:13,319 --> 01:11:15,150
And what do you fear?

780
01:11:16,021 --> 01:11:20,924
What? Now? With Superman dead,
and you're on my team?

781
01:11:21,393 --> 01:11:25,693
It's like you're the best power
forward ever. What's to fear?

782
01:11:39,378 --> 01:11:43,906
<i>All that remains of</i>
<i>Krypton's energy is yours.</i>

783
01:11:44,683 --> 01:11:46,344
<i>After it is gone...</i>

784
01:11:46,552 --> 01:11:50,010
<i>... you will belong solely</i>
<i>to your new home.</i>

785
01:11:51,357 --> 01:11:55,657
<i>If our dying planet can</i>
<i>save your life, my son...</i>

786
01:11:56,729 --> 01:11:59,163
<i>... we have not died in vain.</i>

787
01:13:05,531 --> 01:13:08,364
- Where is the woman?
- You'll never find her.

788
01:13:08,700 --> 01:13:12,466
If you will not tell me,
I will hurt people.

789
01:13:33,692 --> 01:13:35,956
Stop! Don't do it, the people!

790
01:14:34,086 --> 01:14:35,883
All right, stop! That's enough!

791
01:14:36,288 --> 01:14:37,721
That's enough!

792
01:14:37,923 --> 01:14:39,982
You win. I'll take you to her.

793
01:15:11,890 --> 01:15:14,256
- Where is she?
- Far away from here and safe.

794
01:15:15,160 --> 01:15:16,991
Don't go in, she's not in there!

795
01:19:17,669 --> 01:19:19,933
We've gotta tone down
these headlines.

796
01:19:20,138 --> 01:19:23,938
Tone down our headlines?
That's all the common man reads!

797
01:19:24,176 --> 01:19:29,113
- We can do with less sensationalism.
- Less sensational papers go broke.

798
01:19:29,414 --> 01:19:33,714
I thought I taught you long ago that
the business of newspapers is business.

799
01:19:33,919 --> 01:19:35,079
No, Daddy...

800
01:19:35,287 --> 01:19:37,346
...our business is journalism.

801
01:19:37,856 --> 01:19:40,051
We can't keep being
so irresponsible...

802
01:19:40,258 --> 01:19:42,453
...or we'll lead everyone
into disaster.

803
01:19:42,661 --> 01:19:44,652
Don't be overdramatic,
young lady.

804
01:19:44,863 --> 01:19:48,026
What kind of disaster could
we possibly help bring about?

805
01:19:50,435 --> 01:19:51,424
Lacy!

806
01:21:24,663 --> 01:21:26,028
What's going on? Hey!

807
01:21:42,347 --> 01:21:45,316
Are you sure you know what
you're doing, Mr. White?

808
01:21:45,550 --> 01:21:46,778
Well...

809
01:21:48,420 --> 01:21:50,251
Here comes Mr. Warfield.

810
01:21:50,889 --> 01:21:52,880
You better have a good explanation...

811
01:21:53,091 --> 01:21:56,060
...or else you'll be talking
to your lawyers from jail.

812
01:21:56,261 --> 01:21:58,752
You know, I'm not a tycoon.

813
01:21:58,964 --> 01:22:00,727
I'm just an old reporter.

814
01:22:00,932 --> 01:22:03,400
But I've read enough
in my own newspaper...

815
01:22:03,602 --> 01:22:06,662
...about hostile takeovers
at big companies.

816
01:22:06,871 --> 01:22:09,635
You, Mr. Warfield, must have
been asleep at the wheel.

817
01:22:09,874 --> 01:22:12,502
Because I've convinced
the bankers of this city...

818
01:22:12,744 --> 01:22:17,010
...that our <i>Daily Planet</i> should be
treated like a natural resource...

819
01:22:17,215 --> 01:22:19,206
...protected from predators.

820
01:22:19,517 --> 01:22:23,578
I convinced them to lend me the money.
I bought the outstanding shares.

821
01:22:23,788 --> 01:22:28,521
And you, Mr. Warfield,
are now a minority shareholder.

822
01:22:29,728 --> 01:22:31,059
Everyone, back to work.

823
01:22:31,630 --> 01:22:33,029
Way to tell him, chief!

824
01:22:35,533 --> 01:22:38,229
Well, I'm sorry.
You win some and you lose some.

825
01:22:38,436 --> 01:22:41,200
Now this is what I call a newspaper.

826
01:22:41,439 --> 01:22:43,600
Compliments of <i>The Daily Planet.</i>

827
01:22:44,042 --> 01:22:46,704
- Have a nice day. We did it!
- We're back!

828
01:22:51,483 --> 01:22:53,576
- Hi, am I late?
- Hi, how you doing?

829
01:22:53,785 --> 01:22:57,482
It must've been some effort for
you to drag yourself out of bed.

830
01:22:57,689 --> 01:23:01,181
I'm feeling a lot better.
I had a visit from a good nurse.

831
01:23:01,393 --> 01:23:04,726
It must've been good medicine because
she said you were really ill.

832
01:23:04,929 --> 01:23:08,695
Sometimes all you need is loving
attention from the right person.

833
01:23:08,900 --> 01:23:10,595
Glad you're back, Clark.

834
01:23:10,802 --> 01:23:13,862
And remember I am covering
Superman's press conference.

835
01:23:14,072 --> 01:23:17,735
- Just tape reactions from the crowd.
- Reactions, okay.

836
01:23:18,343 --> 01:23:19,310
Oh, dear.

837
01:23:19,544 --> 01:23:21,341
Guess I need a tape recorder, huh?

838
01:23:21,546 --> 01:23:22,535
- Be right back.
- Clark.

839
01:23:22,781 --> 01:23:25,648
Same old Mr. Kent.
He'll never change.

840
01:23:25,850 --> 01:23:27,511
I hope not.

841
01:23:36,261 --> 01:23:39,458
- How you doing, Superman?
- Lois, good to see you again.

842
01:23:39,664 --> 01:23:41,325
Good to see you too.

843
01:23:41,533 --> 01:23:42,830
Morning, gentlemen.

844
01:23:43,268 --> 01:23:44,428
Excuse me.

845
01:23:45,003 --> 01:23:45,833
Thank you.

846
01:23:46,504 --> 01:23:50,167
Once more, we survived the threat
of war and found a fragile peace.

847
01:23:51,109 --> 01:23:54,044
I thought I could give you
freedom from war but...

848
01:23:54,245 --> 01:23:57,112
...I was wrong.
It's not mine to give.

849
01:23:58,650 --> 01:24:00,481
We're still a young planet.

850
01:24:01,019 --> 01:24:03,852
There are galaxies out there...

851
01:24:04,122 --> 01:24:07,649
...other civilizations for us
to meet, to learn from.

852
01:24:08,259 --> 01:24:10,454
What a brilliant future we could have.

853
01:24:10,729 --> 01:24:13,823
And there will be peace when
the people of the world...

854
01:24:14,032 --> 01:24:15,522
...want it so badly...

855
01:24:15,734 --> 01:24:18,897
...their governments will
have to give it to them.

856
01:24:21,306 --> 01:24:24,139
I wish you could see the Earth
the way that I see it...

857
01:24:24,375 --> 01:24:28,038
...because when you really look
at it, it's just one world.

858
01:24:32,250 --> 01:24:33,877
Do you think he'll find us?

859
01:24:34,085 --> 01:24:37,452
Never. We'll lay low for a while...

860
01:24:37,655 --> 01:24:40,886
...a couple of years.
I'll come up with a new plan.

861
01:24:41,626 --> 01:24:44,060
Good thing I bought my drums.

862
01:24:57,776 --> 01:25:00,336
Uncle Lex,
you're not gonna believe this...

863
01:25:00,578 --> 01:25:02,546
...but it's Superman!
- Superman!

864
01:25:07,585 --> 01:25:11,248
- Hey, this rocks!
- Morning, Father.

865
01:25:11,456 --> 01:25:14,152
This kid's been under a bad
influence. Can you help?

866
01:25:14,359 --> 01:25:17,021
- Every boy can be helped.
- I think you're right.

867
01:25:17,228 --> 01:25:19,219
- Good luck, son.
- Come with me, friend.

868
01:25:19,430 --> 01:25:21,557
You wouldn't happen
to have a drum set?

869
01:25:21,766 --> 01:25:24,599
Hey, Mozart's back!

870
01:25:29,574 --> 01:25:32,475
- Duane, Mozart's back!
- I see him, Bubba!

871
01:25:34,746 --> 01:25:36,111
Shut up!

872
01:25:37,115 --> 01:25:40,312
- All right, take him away.
- Thank you. Come on, Luthor.

873
01:25:41,152 --> 01:25:44,644
- Just one thing, how did you beat him?
- High school physics.

874
01:25:44,923 --> 01:25:46,914
I had time to figure out...

875
01:25:47,125 --> 01:25:50,822
...that if it was born from the sun,
that had to be its energy.

876
01:25:51,029 --> 01:25:53,998
- Is the world gonna be vaporized?
- No, Luthor.

877
01:25:54,199 --> 01:25:57,430
It's as it always was, on the brink,
with good fighting evil.

878
01:25:57,635 --> 01:25:58,897
See you in 20.


